 my sudden death and hid my soul from others.”<br><br>“Ranger, have you ever experienced pain?”<br><br>“Yes, many times,” Cendarien replied.<br><br>“Then image that but one thousand times greater.  Your precious Sorrowblade placed me in a rather unpleasing predicament.”<br><br>Cendarien laughed, “It was only fair.  You killed her father.”<br><br>“I killed her father because it had to be done, not because I wanted too.  But, that is history.”<br><br>Cendarien asked again, “What of this reward?  What could the gods be granting for the life of one half elf.”<br><br>“Resurrection,” the voice replied.  “The ultimate of all rewards.”<br><br>“You’re planning on being reborn when you slay Belana,” Cendarien took a step forward.<br><br>“Yes, it will be a glorious day.”<br><br>“You know I won’t let that happen,” Cendarien took another step forward.<br><br>Laughter echoed around the ranger.  It came from all different directions.  The reverberations off the cave walls made the laughter seemed louder and more distant that what it was.  Cendarien felt something in front of him.  The voice spoke again, and Cendarien could hear it loud and clear.  It was from right in front of him.<br><br>“I’m sorry, but only the living can kill me, and from what I know, in the next couple minutes you won’t be part of that order any more.”<br><br>( Back In Odus )<br><br>Inien felt the heat of the fire pass around him.  The flames escaped the void around Inien and engulfed a nearby bookcase.  A small fire began to burn inside.<br><br>“What the hell are you doing Phel,” Inien stood strong in the doorway.  Phelsuma was just finishing her incantation from the fireball that left her hands.<br><br>“I guess I underestimated your powers wizard.  But, the one thing you won’t be able to avoid is my blade,” Phelsuma withdrew a scimitar from a side sheathe.<br><br>Inien looked back at the fire, he raised his hand quickly and soon a huge wind blew through the opening of the door sending pages and books flying in different directions, but the fire was put out.  Inien stepped outside, “If it is a duel you are looking for, then I will have to decline.  I disdain from fighting with weapons forged by the hands of flesh.”<br><br>“Then this will be a short adventure for me,” Phelsuma charged Inien.  Inien held his hands out in front of him.  A long wooden staff appeared out of thin air.  He grabbed the middle of it and placed it down, horizontal with the ground pointing towards Phelsuma.<br><br>Phelsuma swung her sword in an upward attack sending a vibration through the staff.  Inien held on tightly and brought the weapon back down to block Phelsuma’s follow up attack.  Inien found himself on the defensive quickly.  She brought her blade back down but Inien matched it.  Her sword cleaved a notch in the middle of the staff sending small shards of wood flying.  Inien pushed her back, both combatants sat staring at each other a couple feet apart.<br><br>“I ask that you stop this foolishness Phel.  I will not be responsible for what happens to you if you do not heed my word,” Inien commanded.<br><br>“Your such a fool Inien.  Your time has run out grand wizard.  It is time for you to become a memory.”<br><br>Inien shook his head, “I don’t think so.”<br><br>Phelsuma smiled and reared back for her next attack but suddenly a small creature flew down and grabbed onto her head.  The sounds of Phelsuma and the creature screaming were all that could be understood.  The creature flapped its small wings as if trying to lift Phelsuma off the ground.  Phelsuma struggled with the creature for a little bit but soon gained the upper hand.  She made enough room between her head and the creature that she was able to expulse a small bolt of energy sending the small creature to the ground in front of her.<br><br>“Pardon the intrusion, but this imp must die,” Phelsuma placed her sword high above her head.<br><br>Inien’s eyes became white as snow.  Loose dirt and leaves began to vibrate around him and soon his body was encased in a white fire, “You leave him alone!”<br><br>Phelsuma glanced at the flame-encased wizard.  She gasped suddenly as she realized she had taken her eyes off of him for to long.  A ball of ice began to form in front of Inien.  It rotated and pulsed in a white glow.  Phelsuma had no time to react before the ice comet was upon her.  An explosion of cold struck Phelsuma sending her flying back into the small hut that Inien had crafted and through an open window.  The sound of glass breaking was muffled in the explosion of energy.<br><br>Inien’s mana calmed down.  His eyes refocused.  Inien ran over to the small creature, “Muffin!  Muffin, are you all right?”<br><br>The small imp shook its small head.<br><br>“Good! Now where did that druid go,” Inien walked towards his hut.  He peered through the window and noticed a body lying crumpled up against the wall.  He stepped up and over the windowsill and through the debris in the room to get a closer look.  Phelsuma’s body lay unconscious.<br><br>“Now what?” Inien asked himself.  Muffin flew up through the broken window obviously hurt from Phelsuma’s attack.  He was flying with a limp.<br><br>Inien looked down at Phelsuma’s body again but noticed something odd.  He bent over to touch her but he quickly withdrew his hand.  Phelsuma’s image began to shimmer.  Her likeness began to melt away revealing someone else.  Inien watched intensely to see who was hiding under the false disguise of Phelsuma.  It didn’t take long for him to recognize who it was and he gasped.<br><br>“Aianya!”<br> <p><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~blackpoint/AnimationEQ.gif" height=85 width=468 alt="Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue" border=0></a></p><span class=m><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bebonmoon.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blackpointsorrowbladethistletongue>Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 