s impossible that I could ever turn down this opportunity.”<br><br>“I would hate to disappoint,” Blackpoint returned.  She glanced around to see if anyone else was patrolling the streets at this time.  There was no movement anywhere.  She thought of her training and the many battles she had been involved with.  Her style of fighting could not be matched by those that wield a single weapon, Belana would strike two or three times before her assailant could ever deliver there first blow.  She was still worried though.  It had been so long since she had actually dueled someone that was actually of a higher skill than her.  Zaboxx had shown her many times defeat.  They had sparred many times in their adventures but each time Zaboxx always found the upper hand.<br><br>“Your scared,” Zaboxx said.  “Your scared to lose, aren’t you?”<br><br>“I don’t have that option,” Belana replied.<br><br>“I know if I was in your situation I would be scared too.  I mean, to think that with your failure, your precious leader will also fall to my sword and the Shadows would be leaderless.  Broken.  Without Kelwin you would not even be associated with a name such as the Shadows.”<br><br>“The Shadows have undertaken a wound like that way before you ever decided to try Zaboxx.  I wish you be clear on your intensions.  Why are you doing this?  What is your motivation for turning your back on the ones that once called you brother?”<br><br>“Brother?” Zaboxx laughed.  “Look at me Belana! I am a Tier’Dal.  I am not like your other brothers and sisters in your band.  I am dark elf.  I will and always will be an outcast amongst everyone.  Strife is something I have learned to accept.  The bitter realism of this world prevents me from ever enjoying life.”<br><br>“And how does killing us satisfy your plans?” Belana lost her fighting spirit.  She let her hands rest at her side.<br><br>The wind kicked up once more blowing Belana’s hair again.  She soon wished to cut herself free of the bother on top of her head.<br><br>“Satisfy?” Zaboxx answered but was soon unsure of himself.  He drew a puzzled look on his face.  He opened his mouth to speak but no words came out.  He dropped his weapon to the ground and grabbed onto his head.  Zaboxx looked straight out at Belana and pointed at her, and he fell.<br><br>Belana watched.  She ran towards him but stopped.  She knew that Zaboxx might be laying bait for her.  She called out for him but she got no reply.  Belana brought her daggers up in front of her chest for protection.  She hovered above him, she made sure that his weapon was far from his reach.  She knelt down and shook him with from side to side.<br><br>“Zaboxx?” Belana shook him again.  “Zaboxx?”<br><br>She peered back towards Kelwin.  He still lay motionless on the floor.  She stood up and raced over towards him.  She pushed the shield off the top of him and cradled him forward so she could get a good look at his wound.   She could still see the shaft of the arrow still embedded in his back.  She grabbed the shaft with her free hand and pulled.  The sounds that followed were not something Belana could describe but the sudden release of the arrow from Kelwin’s body jolted him alive.  He gasped for air as the pain bolted through his body once more.  He opened his eyes and turned his head to face Belana.<br><br>He whispered to her, “Place my hand over my wound?”<br><br>Belana complied and moved one of Kelwin’s arms arms to reach behind him.  She rolled out his fingers and covered the wound with his now open palm.  Kelwin casted a quick heal and soon the open wound was gone.  Again he casted a quick spell that brought back the strength that he had lost.  The crafty ranger was soon back on his feet in the matter of seconds.<br><br>Kelwin looked over at the Zaboxx’s body, “Is he dead?”<br><br>Belana answered, “No, he is not.  He just fell over.  As if a great weight suddenly weighed down upon him.  I lifted not one finger.”<br><br>“That is good then,” Kelwin replied, “Because if you two would have engaged in battle I doubt I would be speaking to you right now.”  He turned and walked over towards Zaboxx’s body.<br><br>Belana knew that Kelwin was right.  The thought of her own death though never bothered her.  It was inevitable.  She knew one day that her life would cease to exist.  The Sorrowblade name would die with her.  She quickly shook loose the thoughts of death and doubt and followed Kelwin.<br> <p><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~blackpoint/AnimationEQ.gif" height=85 width=468 alt="Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue" border=0></a></p><span class=m><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bebonmoon.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blackpointsorrowbladethistletongue>Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> at: 5/4/02 6:16:16 pm<br></i></span><hr size=1><span class=m> Posts: <b>388</b>  </span></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bebonmoon.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blackpointsorrowbladethistletongue>Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> </span><br> <span class=usertitle>Melee Elder</span><br> <BR><img src=http://ebonmoon.com/images/members/blackpoint.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top width=80% class=m><span class=title>   Re: Part VII - Beginning of The End</span><br><span class=m><font color=#778899>Posted: 5/8/02 5:57:00 pm</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>   &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/febonmoonfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=33.topic&index=2><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/reply.gif border=0 width=20 height=20 alt="reply to this message" align=absmiddle></a>   <hr size=1> Belana and Kelwin stood above their fallen comrade in arms.  Zaboxx still rested on the ground unmoving. Belana kept running the scenario in her head over and over.  The last motions of him pointing at her before he fell, she imaged his hand again.<br><br>Kelwin reached down and picked up the weapon that Zaboxx had drawn on Belana.  It was a simple longsword.  The craftsmanship was beautiful.  Kelwin took a second to admire the blade, the he pointed it down towards Zaboxx.<br><br>Belana looked at Kelwin, “What are you doing?”<br><br>Kelwin replied, “To attack a fellow member in our guild without just cause is an act worthy of death.  It will be quick and painless for him.”<br><br>“What!” Belana exclaimed.<br><br>“Need I remind you of the arrow that was put in my back?  How about that guard over there,” Kelwin pointed towards the full armored guard that laid still.  “He would have killed you too if he hadn’t past out.”<br><br>Belana bit her lip.  She couldn’t let this happen.  Kelwin lined the sword up with Zaboxx’s head.  His strike would be quick and clean.  He shook his head in disapproval of his actions but duty came first in his life.<br><br>“You bare witness to this Belana.  I will need you to explain why I did this to the council of Felwithe and to the Shadows.  They will surely want to know what happened to their guardsman.”<br><br>Belana didn’t reply.  The image of Zaboxx’s before he fell kept flashing into her head.  Over and over the image past through her head, her visions were swimming around that one point in time.  She kept seeing his hand.  His hand.  His hand.  She glanced up at Kelwin, who was just finishing some religious rhetoric.  His hand.  Belana couldn’t shake it.<br><br>Kelwin finished.  He brought the blade up over his head and closed his eyes.<br><br>[ Back in Inien’s house ]<br><br>Inien stood in disbelief.  He had seen pictures of the one they called Aianya.  She had been the one that started a band of brothers and sisters he now called family.  In his haste judgment of the figure it turned towards him and opened it’s eyes.  It brought its left leg up and kicked Inien away from her.  Inien went sprawling into the wall and fell against a bookcase.  The sudden impact jolted the bookcase loose from its foundation.  It began to lean forward and multiple tomes began to fall out quickly burying Inien.  The figure stood up and walked towards the bookcase.  With a quick shove the bookcase came crashing down upon Inien burying him in books and wood.  A cloud of dust kicked up.  The figure glanced in-between the bookshelves and could see a hand jutting out from the pile.  The figure watched it for a couple seconds and soon walked away seeing no life twitch inside.<br><br>The figures image flickered again.  Its skin soon melted away and took another form.  The figure walked over to a nearby closet and removed a robe of Inien’s.  It undressed from its current garb and placed the robe over its body.  Looking into a cracked mirror, the figure smiled in satisfaction.  The abstract vision filled the mirror with an image familiar to itself.  The image of the fallen wizard, Inien Astralwrath.<br><br>[ In an underground cave ]<br><br>Cendarien felt himself get pushed back down towards the ground.  His vision still hadn’t cleared up. Shaking his head, he again asked his captor what he or she wanted.<br><br>“If you’re going to kill me then do so now.  I will not be played with like an animal!” Cendarien rose to his feet once more.<br><br>The voice laughed, “In due time ranger.  I am readying your death as we speak.”<br><br>“I’m tired of these games!” Cendarien found the wall again and began to follow it.  He thought maybe if he followed the wall it would lead the cavern’s mouth.  He hoped he just picked the right direction.<br><br>The voice returned, “Then why don’t I shed some light on the matter for you?”<br><br>A blinding flash encased Cendarien.  The cave lit up as if one thousand torches had been lit.  Cendarien opened his eyes and realized he could  see once more.  He checked around him quickly and could see that he stood inside a large bowl.  He laughed quickly realizing he would have walked in circles until he past out from weariness.  Inside the bowl were a couple piles of bones and a dark object on the other end.<br><br>The voice came again,  but more direct.  Cendarien glanced above him and could see an image dressed in armor.  The chest piece bore the crest of the Felwithe Clerics.  The long white hair draped down around her head and down her neck.  Cendarien gasped!<br><br>“Willisa?” Cendarien stepped back to get a better look.  His elven eyes were not deceiving him.  He was seeing what was fact.  He was looking at the undead body of Willisa Sorrowblade, his wife’s sister.<br><br>She spoke, “This will be a grand event.  You see, I have found a couple of my favorite skeletons to occupy your time while I’m gone.  Unfortunately, your time won’t be that long.”  Willisa glanced down at the bottom of the bowl.  The three piles of bones began to reanimate themselves.<br><br>“But don’t think I’m unfair.  Three against one is not what I had intended, I thought I would rid myself of another that began to get a little close to the truth before I could act.”  Willisa stood up pointed towards the dark object on the other side of the bowl.  The shroud lifted off revealing a familiar face.<br><br>Willisa casted a quick heal spell setting life back in the inanimate figure.  She stood up off the ground and quickly glanced around.<br><br>“You two enjoy.  I must be going,” and with that Willisa walked out of site of Cendarien and his other captive.<br><br>Cendarien quickly ran across the bowl dodging the re-animating skeletons.  They hadn’t yet completed reforming.  He came across the female.<br><br>“Phelsuma?”<br><br>“Ow, ow, ow!  Where am I?” Phelsuma looked towards Cendarien.<br><br>Cendarien looked out again amongst the walking undead.  They had finished with their reforming and the unhinged skulls rotated around looking towards the two.  They raised their hands like mindless zombies and began to walk towards the two shadows.<br> <p><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~blackpoint/AnimationEQ.gif" height=85 width=468 alt="Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue" border=0></a></p><span class=m><i></i></span><hr size=1><span class=m> Posts: <b>399</b>  </span></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bebonmoon.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blackpointsorrowbladethistletongue>Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> </span><br> <span class=usertitle>Melee Elder</span><br> <BR><img src=http://ebonmoon.com/images/members/blackpoint.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top width=80% class=m><span class=title>   Re: Part VII - Beginning of The End</span><br><span class=m><font color=#778899>Posted: 5/15/02 2:58:26 am</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>   &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/febonmoonfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=33.topic&index=3><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/reply.gif border=0 width=20 height=20 alt="reply to this message" align=absmiddle></a>   <hr size=1> Phelsuma gained her bearings and stood up next to Cendarien.  A sudden pain shot from her chest that caused her to wince.  She quickly wondered what could of caused such a terrible shock.  Phelsuma took a glance out amongst the incoming gang of undead.  She looked over to Cendarien.  She laughed inside.<br><br>“These are no match for us Cendarien,” Phelsuma looked back over and extended her arms.  She began to chant the words that only druids could speak and soon a blast of fire encased one of the skeletons.  It erupted in an explosion of bone shards.  Cendarien and Phelsuma covered their faces quickly to protect their eyes from the splinters.<br><br>Cendarien looked back over to Phelsuma, “Your right.”  Cendarien hands began to radiate a red fire.  He charged after one of the last few skeletons and struck out with his fist.  The skeleton recoiled from the blow and fell down.<br><br>“I’ll finish it off,” Phelsuma again casted her magics and soon the second skeleton was no more.<br><br>The final skeleton slowly walked towards the two.  Its bones creaked with age.  It arms were still outstretched as if it was begging to be placed in pieces like the others, and soon it was.<br><br>“That wasn’t so hard,” Cendarien looked over towards Phelsuma.<br><br>“I know.  I can’t believe I let that witch get the best of me,” Phelsuma answered.<br><br>“Witch?” Cendarien walked over to the walls and took a chance at climbing out.<br><br>“Yeah, that thing masquerading as Whitepoint.  And I wasn’t alone.”<br><br>Cendarien scaled down from the wall, “Who was with you?”<br><br>Phelsuma glanced over at Cendarien and watched his attempts to climb up the bowl they were laying in.  She walked over to him and held out her hand, “Grab hold.”<br><br>Cendarien complied and soon a powerful force threw the both of them up and outside the bowl.  They landed with the gentleness of a baby’s gaze.  The perimeter of the bowl was unguarded.  It seemed that they were the only two left in this strange cave.<br><br>“Zaboxx was with me,” Phelsuma broke the silence.  She turned to face Cendarien again who was brushing himself clean of dust and debris.<br><br>“What happened then?”<br><br>“Zaboxx and I were walking through the Burning Woods and we came across a high elf that needed help.  We both stopped to see what we could do and before I knew it Zaboxx was knocked down by something.  I didn’t have much of a chance before I fell to the same.  The last thing I remember was her face,” she rubbed her chest.  The feeling of pain was beginning to throb inside her.  Again, she wondered what she had done to cause such pain.  Or what had been done to her?<br><br>Cendarien looked puzzled, “Then what happened?”<br><br>“I don’t know.  I awoke but couldn’t move.  Everything was dark and for some reason I couldn’t cast up until now.  It seems that someone she had locked my powers but unlocked them.”<br><br>Cendarien thought for a moment, “Wait a sec.  Why would she unlock your power?”<br><br>“What do you mean?”<br><br>“You were just laying there when I was tossed down here.  She casted a spell and soon you were moving and up and about.  Then she left.”<br><br>Phelsuma thought for a moment, “Your kind of right.  Why would she do that if she wanted to rid herself of us.”<br><br>Cendarien shook his head, “This is getting thicker and thicker by the minute.”<br><br>“Well, we need to find Zaboxx.  If he is hear.  Do you sense him?”<br><br>Cendarien closed his eyes for a moment.  He bent down low and then straightened himself up again, “No, I don’t.  But I do pick up one other instead of us in hear.”<br><br>Phelsuma walked away from Cendarien, “Your right.  I can feel it too.”<br><br>“Let us see who this is then,” Cendarien began to run in the direction of the scent.  Phelsuma followed.<br><br><br>[ Back in Felwithe ]<br><br><br>Kelwin held the blade over his head.  He made the decision in his head and brought it down.  His hands stopped.  Kelwin quickly opened his eyes to see what held his blade.  A single dagger blocked the path between the blade and Zaboxx.  Kelwin glanced over and could see Belana holding the dagger.  His eyes grew wide with astonishment.<br><br>“What are you doing?” Kelwin relaxed and brought the blade down to his side.<br><br>“I think we are acting on false pretences.  Zaboxx didn’t mean to do this,” Belana replied.<br><br>“You can’t be serious.  Is the hole in my armor not enough proof?” Kelwin looked angered.<br><br>“You don’t understand.  When he fell over he offered his hand out to me.  At first I thought he was pointing at something but when I look at it again he was actually holding his hand out for me.”<br><br>“And that means?” Kelwin asked.<br><br>“He was asking for help.  Something isn’t right here.  Where ever I am the truth is masked by falsehoods.  This whole fight was set up but somehow Zaboxx’s strong will broke the hold on whatever was holding him.  There are darker forces here in Felwithe.  They haven’t revealed themselves yet though.”<br><br>The sound of clapping echoed from behind them.  Belana and Kelwin turned to see who it was that was clapping.  A hooded figure appeared out from the darkness.  The figures white hands could be seen in the light that only the stars and moons provided.<br><br>“You are wise beyond your years Belana Sorrowblade.  You should have dabbled in the arcane arts instead of sneaking in the shadows.”<br><br>Belana reached down for her weapons quickly and withdrew them.  Kelwin followed suit with the long sword.  <br><br>“Belana Sorrowblade.  Rogue of the Dagger.  Wife to Cendarien Thistletongue.  Sister to Willisa Sorrowblade and Aaeon Stormbringer.  You have quite the family tree.”<br><br>Belana shouted, “What is your game?  How do you know of me so well?”<br><br>“This is not the setting I wish to describe to you your fate.  I will bring us to a more,” the figure paused, “suitable location.”<br><br>Belana and Kelwin didn’t have time to react before they were teleported away.  The sudden blackness overcame them quickly but soon they were surrounded by torchlight.<br><br>They found themselves inside a cave.  The walls were lined with torches.  Kelwin looked to his sides and noticed that Zaboxx was also with them, although he was still unconscious.<br><br>The robed figure emerged again, “Now, this is more like it.  I would hate to slaughter the whole town of Felwithe with one fell swoop of my hand but I know that the other gods would not allow that.  At least, not right now.”<br><br>“Other gods?” Kelwin asked.<br><br>“Ah, Kelwin Jumala.  Ranger of Tunare.  It is good to see that you have not lost your will to speak.  It would be wise though that you hold your tongue.  I have no quarrel with you and if you play your cards right you might be blessed to keep that pitiful life of yours.”<br><br>Kelwin did not answer.  He could sense a great power from the figure.  He just didn’t hope that it was who he thought it was.<br><br>The figure’s head turned towards Belana again, “It is to bad that Zaboxx refused my will.  I crafted him from my own mind.  A natural born warrior.  A warrior infused with the art of every known weapon to my mind.  With the added strength of necromancy he could have been invincible in my army.  It is unfortunate he did not work out.”<br><br>“So you were controlling him?” Belana returned.<br><br>“Again,” the figure chuckled to himself.  A dark, ominous tone filled the caves.<br><br>“Did you just hear that?” Cendarien turned towards Phelsuma.<br><br>Phelsuma stopped running, “I think so.  We have a bigger problem though than that.”<br><br>“What?”<br><br>“I sense five more in this cave.  And I know who three of them are.”<br><br>Cendarien used his acute tracking skills and gasped, “It’s Kelwin.”<br><br>“Yes, and Zaboxx and . . .”<br><br>“Belana!” Cendarien shouted.  He turned and ran as fast as he could.<br><br>“Yes, I was controlling him.  I was controlling him and another.”<br><br>“Another,” Kelwin asked<br><br>“Yes, someone I made just in case my plan was met with failure.”<br><br>“Your plan?” Belana looked over to Kelwin who had the same expression on his face.  She glanced over at Zaboxx but still saw no movement.<br><br>“Well.  I hate to give it away but since your at the end of your existence I will fill you in.”  The figure removed the hood from its face and revealed a figure that was very familiar to them.”<br><br>“Inien!  What are you doing?” Belana yelled.<br><br>“I am not your friend Inien.  He is dead.  I have merely taken his form.  I needed one more element to finish the deal, but I will explain for you are probably very confused.”<br><br>The figure began to pace, “Your sister’s body is now possessed by the demon that you thought you killed in the plains of the Karana’s not so long ago.  Unknown to any living being, the demon that now calls himself Darkpoint was brought before Cazic Thule.  He begged for a second chance.  Cazic granted him that chance but made a deal with the demon.  He would grant Darkpoint the dead body of one being of his choice.”<br><br>“So he chose my sister’s body,” Belana looked disgusted.<br><br>“Correct young one.  He did choose your sister’s body.  But, unknown to even him that something else was in the works.  Cazic approached Innorrukk and asked for his help in the matter.  Cazic does not like you very much.  Sins of the father maybe.”<br><br>“My father is dead!”<br><br>“And that is why Cazic is upset with you.  You see Belana, your father was supposedly no holy man.  He was agnostic, just like you are.  But, it was a lie.  Rogues don’t follow deities.  You were brought up that way and he was too.”<br><br>Cendarien and Phelsuma stopped.  They could hear a voice talking.<br><br>“Your father believed in that wretch Tunare.  The same idol that your sister, Willisa worshipped.  But, when your father died, his soul went to Tunare.  Tunare made your father a captain in her armies in a war that you living folk do not see.  It is raged in the skies and far below the ground.  Your father has been the biggest thorn in his side since his death.”<br><br>Belana smiled.  The sudden thought of her father in battle suddenly made her happy.  She wished to see him at least one more time to say things that she had always wanted to say to him.<br><br>“And that brings us to you,” the figure stopped moving, “I was sent from my Lord Innorrukk to find myself someone that was close to you.  Someone in this family you hold so dear.  So, I chose Phelsuma and Zaboxx.  I possessed their minds in a rainy night in the Burning Woods on Kunark.  They will never know the unspeakable acts they perpetrated against their fellow man.”<br><br>Cendarien looked over to Phelsuma who grew pale.  She brought her hand to her mouth and closed her eyes.  The thoughts of her harming anyone quickly made her grow ill.<br><br>“Phelsuma and Zaboxx finished off your half-sister Aaeon the other night to be exact.  It was a grizzly affair if my accounts of it are correct.  You can blame Zaboxx for the killing blow.”<br><br>Belana soon felt sorrow strike deep within her heart.  She had forgotten all about Aaeon.  The last remaining shard of her family.  <br><br>Phelsuma gasped at the thought of killing someone.<br><br>“But, she could not finish off Inien like I had asked.  Inien was too strong and defeated her.  In the debris of the battle, I traded places with Phelsuma and took a form that would shock the wizard into fright.  Then I finished the wizard off.”<br><br>A sudden pain shot through Phelsuma’s chest.  A stimulant to the truth that this figure had said.  Again, the thoughts of her harming Inien and Aaeon caused great depression inside her.  Her heart became weighted and soon she in tears.<br><br>Cendarien looked over to her and gripped her shoulder, “This was not your free will.  Be free of you demons.  We will be in action shortly and I will need all your wits.”<br><br>Phelsuma didn’t reply.<br><br>“Inien,” Belana whispered, “It can’t be true.”<br><br>“I used the guise of becoming the vision of Innorrukk to charm them into helping me.  It took a strong hold on both and they reported to me as if they were talking to the exalted one himself.  It is true rogue.  Everyone you have ever cared for is dead.  All except that ranger of yours but if my memory serves me correct he will not be walking amongst the living for much longer either.”<br><br>“What have you done with Cendarien!” Belana shouted with a rush of strength.  Grief stricken as she was, she couldn’t let anything else happen to her friends.<br><br>“He is of no concern.  Let me finish my story first,” the figure paused and took a step closer to Belana, “You see, Cazic and Innorrukk are betting for your soul.  When you die Belana, your soul will be, well, up for grabs, as they say.  You will become a prisoner and serve the god that chooses you.  Your strength will lead the dark armies to overrun those that Tunare and her friends battle against us.  You will serve us.”<br><br>Belana hung her head down.  Her life had seemed so ordinary up until a couple months ago.  The sudden facts were swirling in her head so quickly that her judgment was crowded.  She rose her head and looked straight at the figure, “I will never serve you or either of those two gods.”<br><br>“You can say all you want rogue, but you will turn just like everyone else before you,” the figure soon melted away its exterior to take on a more natural form.  Inien’s face melted away revealing a dark elf exterior.  “But, it is not my job to kill you.  It is someone else’s.”  The figure motioned with his arm for someone to come.<br><br>Belana and Kelwin watched as another figure walked into the light of the torches.  The face was all to familiar to both of them.  The time for a final confrontation loomed overhead.<br><br>The figure spoke again, “This should be a battle worthy of my viewing.  I can’t wait to see what kind of strength you both shall portray for both of you will be in our armies soon enough.”<br><br>Belana looked into the eyes of her sister.  They were white and emotionless.  Her hair was matted and dirty, unlike how it was when she was still alive.  The white adoring face she once had was masked by a shade of gray.<br><br>“I will have life once more,” Darkpoint spoke.<br><br>Belana who had held her daggers loosely quickly gripped them.  She was still dressed in her street attire.  Her quickness could not fail her for one false step would send her to her own misery.<br><br>“And just so there will be no interference,” The figure shot a webbing at Kelwin that sent him to the ground.  He struggled as a white web surrounded his body entrapping him.<br><br>Belana shot a glance at Kelwin but quickly turned towards her sister’s rushing body.  Armed with a sword that was greater than her daggers, Darkpoint charged in.  It seemed the inevitable had reached Belana at last.<br> <p><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~blackpoint/AnimationEQ.gif" height=85 width=468 alt="Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue" border=0></a></p><span class=m><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bebonmoon.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blackpointsorrowbladethistletongue>Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> at: 5/15/02 3:01:41 am<br></i></span><hr size=1><span class=m> Posts: <b>415</b>  </span></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bebonmoon.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blackpointsorrowbladethistletongue>Blackpoint Sorrowblade Thistletongue</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> </span><br> <span class=usertitle>Melee Elder</span><br> <BR><img src=http://ebonmoon.com/images/members/blackpoint.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top width=80% class=m><span class=title>   Re: Part VII - Beginning of The End</span><br><span class=m><font color=#778899>Posted: 5/20/02 3:22:44 am</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>   &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/febonmoonfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=33.topic&index=4><